 "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "subseafloor hydrothermal or vent-wall FT-type synthesis under anoxic reducing conditions"}, "mechanism": "CO2-derived carbon is reduced on magnetite/Fe0 surfaces through Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry to small aldehydes that seed chain growth.", "reasoning": "McCollom et al. (1999) support Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal generation of hydrocarbons and oxygenates that can act as aldehyde precursors, while the deep report identifies acetaldehyde and formaldehyde as essential steps in the leucine precursor hierarchy; this reaction is used as the hydrothermal source of the C1-C2 carbonyl pool."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis from reduced carbon feedstocks", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite/greigite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent mixing-zone conditions, anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Sequential reduction and C-C bond formation among C1 carbonyl species on mineral surfaces produce alpha-keto acid scaffolds, represented here by pyruvate.", "reasoning": "The instructions explicitly include pyruvate synthesis on magnetite/greigite in hydrothermal settings, and the literature report emphasizes proto-metabolic alpha-keto acid networks continuous with modern metabolism. This connection is consistent with Kaur et al. (2024) for keto-acid-centered networks and Barge et al. (2019) for hydrothermal alpha-keto acid to amino acid conversion."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Green-rust analogue reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "343K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide analogue represented by iron mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 10, alkaline hydrothermal vent analogue"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia condenses with the alpha-keto acid and is reduced on iron-rich mineral surfaces to the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "Barge et al. (2019) experimentally demonstrated pyruvate plus ammonia conversion to alanine at 70C and pH 10 in mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides, establishing the general plausibility of hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-keto acids. The present network uses hydrothermal iron mineral agents to remain within the required mineral list while preserving the literature-derived chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Volcanic H2S spark-discharge generation of HCN", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_003", "mol_001", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient to warm volcanic plume conditions", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and sulfide mineral surfaces as deposition/photochemical interfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "electrical discharge in H2S-containing reducing gas mixture; post-discharge dissolution into water"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge in sulfur-rich volcanic gases generates cyanide and radical intermediates that feed aqueous Strecker chemistry after quenching.", "reasoning": "Parker et al. (2011) showed that leucine and isoleucine were generated specifically in H2S-containing Miller-type spark discharge experiments, while Miller and Van Trump (1981) and Ring et al. (1972) support spark-generated HCN as a key precursor to amino acids via Strecker chemistry. Mineral agents here represent realistic surface deposition and photochemical interfaces required by the schema."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Spark/radical and aldol generation of branched aldehydes from formaldehyde and acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 and borate-rich mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV irradiation and wet-dry concentration; sulfur-rich radical chemistry; aldol/recombination cascades"}, "mechanism": "Small aldehydes undergo UV/radical-assisted recombination and aldol chain growth to branched C4-C5 aldehydes, including isobutyraldehyde and isovaleraldehyde.", "reasoning": "The report identifies radical recombination in spark discharge and aldol condensation cascades as the principal ways to build leucine's branched carbon skeleton, with Parker et al. (2011b) specifically invoking H2S-derived radicals and Sutton, Pulletikurti, and Krishnamurthy (2025) arguing that formaldehyde aldol chemistry inevitably generates branched frameworks. This is one of the necessary connective reactions because no single paper demonstrates the full continuous assembly to isovaleraldehyde under one exact setup."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Classical Strecker synthesis of leucine aminonitrile from isovaleraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral surface concentration and adsorption", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous evaporitic pool or volcanic runoff; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "The aldehyde condenses with ammonia to an imine, cyanide adds to form the aminonitrile, yielding leucine aminonitrile as the direct Strecker precursor.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical leucine Strecker route described in the research summary and attributed to Miller and Van Trump (1981), with isotopic/mechanistic support from Chimiak et al. (2022). The specific precursor isovaleraldehyde is explicitly identified in the report as the key branched aldehyde for leucine."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Hydrolysis of leucine aminonitrile to leucine", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous hydrolysis during geothermal cycling or prolonged standing"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolyzes through amide-like intermediates to the racemic amino acid.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles to amino acids is the final step of the classical Strecker pathway to leucine, as summarized from Miller and Van Trump (1981) and discussed mechanistically by Magrino et al. (2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Nickel-catalyzed reductive amination of alpha-ketoisocaproate to leucine", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K", "pressure": "1 atm H2", "catalyst": "Ni/SiO2-Al2O3 or meteoritic Ni-Fe surface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH 8, 18 h, room temperature"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia forms an imine/iminium equivalent with the alpha-keto acid and H2-driven reduction on Ni-containing surfaces furnishes leucine with high amino-acid selectivity.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024) directly demonstrated leucine formation from alpha-ketoisocaproate at 22C, pH 8, 1 atm H2 over Ni/SiO2-Al2O3, Pd/C, and ground Aletai meteorite with yields of 6-84%, making this the strongest direct route in the network."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Proto-metabolic chain extension from pyruvate to alpha-ketoisocaproate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-343K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": "Ni-containing protometabolic metal catalysis", "aqueous": "tr