7", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-343K", "pressure": "1 atm to moderate", "catalyst": "Ni-bearing or meteoritic metal surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "H2-dependent reductive aldol/chain-extension network; anoxic"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-keto-acid network chemistry extends smaller carbonyl/keto-acid units to the branched C6 alpha-keto acid alpha-ketoisocaproate.", "reasoning": "The research identifies alpha-ketoisocaproate as the pivotal leucine precursor and notes that Kaur et al. propose H2-dependent reductive aldol chemistry over nickel catalysts as a continuous proto-metabolic network, but full geochemically realistic demonstration from simple feedstocks remains an open frontier. This step is therefore included as the necessary, explicitly gap-acknowledging connector rather than as a claimed solved reaction (Kaur et al., 2024; Amend & Shock, 1998)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Exogenous meteoritic delivery of leucine into prebiotic pools", "inputs": [], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "variable", "pressure": "ambient after delivery", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "carbonaceous chondrite infall and parent-body inheritance; racemic abiotic input"}, "mechanism": "No synthesis occurs locally; extraterrestrial leucine is delivered and incorporated into the connected prebiotic pool inventory.", "reasoning": "Leucine is confirmed in the Murchison meteorite and related carbonaceous chondrites at ppb-level abundance, so exogenous delivery is a valid source term but not a chemical transformation. This corrects the common mistake of encoding meteorite delivery as a reaction from terrestrial precursors (Cronin et al., 1981; Glavin et al., 2018)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Volcanic spark Strecker route via direct branched aldehyde generation", "description": "H2S-rich spark chemistry ge