nce >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Leucine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network centers leucine synthesis on literature-supported hubs rather than forcing an unsupported one-pot C1-to-leucine route. The best-supported target-forming node is alpha-ketoisocaproate, which is converted to leucine by Ni-catalyzed H2-driven reductive amination under mild conditions. Parallel surface routes produce leucine through Strecker chemistry from isovaleraldehyde via leucine aminonitrile, while hydrothermal settings generate smaller carbon and nitrogen feedstocks, pyruvate, alanine, and reducing conditions that feed surface and biochemical transformations. The branched carbon skeleton problem is handled conservatively using literature-grounded branch intermediates such as isobutyraldehyde and isovaleraldehyde, with explicitly marked speculative but necessary connection steps based on aldol/radical chain-extension proposals discussed in the research. Exogenous meteoritic leucine is represented as environmental availability through a transport-like incorporation reaction rather than an impossible synthetic transformation. Ten distinct pathways are obtained by combining convergent access to isovaleraldehyde, leucine aminonitrile, alpha-ketoisocaproate, and direct exogenous delivery, all feeding the same target.\n\nMOLECULES (15 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_004: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C3H4O3 (pyruvic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C3H7NO2 (alanine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C4H8O (isobutyraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C5H10O (isovaleraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C6H10O3 (alpha-ketoisoc