rted by Cronin et al. and later meteoritic analyses. It is not a synthesis route, but the network explicitly frames it as exogenous delivery into prebiotic pools, which is appropriate and chemically sound.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Clarify transport, concentration, and preservation conditions after meteoritic delivery.\",\n        \"Distinguish more explicitly between endogenous synthesis and exogenous supply in the pathway labeling.\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically strong and chemically mixed. It meets or exceeds the structural requirements: 15 molecule nodes and 16 reaction nodes, several genuine hubs, multiple convergence points, and no obvious isolated subgraphs. Environmental interconnection is also good: hydrothermal reactions generate reduced carbon and pyruvate/alanine feedstocks, surface chemistry produces HCN and Strecker intermediates, and biochemical steps complete leucine formation. The strongest literature-aligned parts are rxn_011 (alpha-ketoisocaproate to leucine by Ni/H2 reductive amination, strongly supported by Kaur et al. 2024), rxn_004 (pyruvate to alanine, supported by Barge et al. 2019), rxn_009-rxn_010 (classical Strecker/hydrolysis logic), and rxn_016 (meteoritic delivery, supported by Cronin et al. 1981). The main deficiencies are concentrated in the branched-carbon construction problem, which the literature itself identifies as the central unresolved challenge. In this network, rxn_006, rxn_007, and especially rxn_015 are too compressed and insufficiently supported experimentally. rxn_008 is somewhat defensible as a network-level abstraction of spark-discharge chemistry, but it should be described more explicitly as such. Literature alignment is moderate rather than excellent because the network correctly centers the best-supported target-forming node